NOVEMBER ISSUE: Who's Fast 2002
----------------------------------------------------

In a new world reframed by terror and war, we continue
to celebrate the acts of innovation, leadership, and
personal challenge that are the hallmark of our Who's
Fast issue and Fast Company. Last week, we brought you
two of these everyday heroes. Today, we present two of
our greatest disrupters ...

DISRUPTER: Stephen Friend | by George Anders
The driving force behind a genomics technology that may
reshape how drug companies fight disease and test new
products is conducting a second experiment: figuring
out whether he can transplant the energy of a startup
into the giant that bought his company.
http://robin.fastcompany.com/cgi-bin/nph-t.pl?U=1785&M=79151&MS=3242

DISRUPTER: Akira Ishikawa | by Paul C. Judge
The semiconductor has been the driving force behind the
digital revolution. Now Akira Ishikawa is looking to
force the revolution into overdrive by creating
semiconductors in the form of spheres instead of chips
-- a breakthrough with truly electrifying implications.
http://robin.fastcompany.com/cgi-bin/nph-t.pl?U=1786&M=79151&MS=3242

Read more from Who's Fast 2002:
http://robin.fastcompany.com/cgi-bin/nph-t.pl?U=1787&M=79151&MS=3242

